memory defines one of the data locations in Solidity that can hold the value temporarily during runtime. memory variables in Solidity can only be declared within methods and are usually used in method parameters. It's a short term variable that cannot be saved on the blockchain; it holds the value only during the execution of a function and its value is destroyed after execution.
Take a look at example function f() in which I declared a pointer using the memory keyword. It will not alter the value of variable User, whereas if it was declared using storage it will change the value of variable User stored on the blockchain and the value will not be destroyed...
struct User {
 string name;
}
User[] users;

function f() external {
 User memory user = users[0]; // create a pointer
 user.name = "example name" // can't change the value of struct User
}

